"Crow Butte." Near Ft. Robinson, Neb. and F.E. & M.V. R.R. -- In battle, the Indians drove the "Crows" up on the mountain and camped on the only approach, intending to kill or starve their enemy. The "Crows" killed and skinned one of their ponies. The hide was made into ropes and used in lowering their ponies and people from opposite side of mountain. The oldest of their number was left to keep up camp fires to deceive their enemy; after three days the old man came down and surrendered and informed them of his tribe's escape. They gave him his liberty for bravery and loyalty to his tribe [graphic].

Flemmings, president of the branch is giving to an appreciative audience high points on campaign procedure. Seated around the speaker's table are L. to R. (facing speaker) Rev. S.T. Alexander, campaign booster; Ernest P. Payne, Jr.; Ernest P. Payne, Sr., Xmas Seal sales chairman; H.L. Humphrey; Mr. and Mrs. Dorsey Adams. Seated L. to R. (back of speaker) R.J. Diamond, 1956 membership campaign director; Emmett Session, director of Labor Division; Rev. H.R. Bradley, was banquet speaker; and Rev. H.T. Wise, church membership campaign director.
